    h1 CSDT UX Research Project
    p The final writeup for a User Experience research project about the Culturally Situated Design Tools website.
    p This project was conducted for SI 432 in U-M's School of Information.
    h2 Introduction
    p The African Fractals portion of the CSDT website is an incredible batch of content and tutorials for any student who wants to learn about how fractal geometry is incorporated into African culture, architecture, art, religion, and more.
    p My goal with this research project is to explore the areas of the site where improvements can be made in order to make the content and tutorials even more digestible, allowing even more students to be impacted by Professor Ron Eglash and his team’s incredibly comprehensive hub of knowledge.
    h2 User Research & Analysis
    h3 Data Collection Plan
    p It was very important for me to obtain the fresh perspective of users who are unfamiliar with the site. Additionally, it was important for me to speak directly with the students that the African Fractals portion of the site is targeting: upper high school students.
    p I was able to recruit a total of three participants who fit this criterion to each participate in a remote usability testing session. For these testing sessions, each participant was provided with a list of tasks and questions to answer that revolved around the African Fractals portion of the CSDT website. I obtained screen and audio recordings of each test which allowed me to re-watch and pluck out the important bits of information for the analysis portion of my research.
    p Unsurprisingly, this left with me with quite a bit of user data to comb through. To make sense of it, I began by following my favorite model of UX data organization and categorization, developed by an ex-VP of User Experience at WeWork, Tomer Sharon. His model is based on the idea that research artifacts like transcripts and screen recordings are not the most useful units of user experience data. Instead, his model looks at things even more granularly. He refers to these granular research insights as “nuggets,” single observations made by users that are gathered through research. Each of these nuggets are then added to a database and tagged with important information that make them easily searchable and capable of being grouped together. I tagged my nuggets to convey two different metrics:
    p •    Which portion of the site the user’s insight was referring to.
    p •    Whether their insight was a positive one, a negative one, a neutral statement, or a suggestion.
    p After plucking out these insights from all three of my participant’s user tests, I ended up with a comprehensive database of user insights that I was able to group and categorize in order to develop my findings and work toward a conclusion.
